The reported issue pertains to the manual creation of a CSV file containing formula-based payloads (e.g., =CMD|' /C calc'!A0) and the subsequent execution of these formulas when the file is opened in spreadsheet software such as Microsoft Excel. This behavior is an expected and intended feature of Excel, which is designed to automatically interpret cell values beginning with characters such as =, +, -, or @ as executable formulas. In this scenario, the payload is neither introduced nor processed by the application, and the application does not generate, modify, or distribute the malicious content. Consequently, there is no application-level security control being bypassed, no trust boundary violation, and no impact to other users via the application. As the observed behavior occurs entirely due to the default functionality of the spreadsheet software and is independent of the application, it does not constitute a valid CSV/Formula Injection vulnerability. Therefore, this finding is considered invalid and can be closed as “Not Applicable.”
